Day 2 case
The following code can be saved as a html file. The code is to demonstrate how to listen for user input and provide immediate feedback, similar to triggering a callback on every keystroke in Python.
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
<style>
input {
padding: 8px;
border: 2px solid #ccc;
border-radius: 4px;
outline: none;
}
input.valid { border-color: green; }
input.invalid { border-color: red; }
#hint { font-size: 14px; color: gray; }
</style>
</head>
<body>
<label>username(>=3 characters):</label>
<input type="text" id="username">
<p id="hint">please input username</p><script>
const input = document.getElementById("username");
const hint = document.getElementById("hint");
input.addEventListener("input", (e) => {
const value = e.target.value.trim();
if (value.length === 0) {
input.classList.remove("valid", "invalid");
hint.textContent = "please input username";
hint.style.color = "gray";
} else if (value.length < 3) {
input.classList.add("invalid");
input.classList.remove("valid");
hint.textContent = `still needs ${3 - value.length} characters`;
hint.style.color = "red";
} else {
input.classList.add("valid");
input.classList.remove("invalid");
hint.textContent = "✓ username available";
hint.style.color = "green";
}
});
</script>
</body>
</html>
1/ HTML Structure
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
<style>
/* CSS */
</style>
</head> <body>
<input type="text" id="username">
<script>
/* JavaScript */
</script>
</body>
</html>
As in Case 1, the CSS is embedded directly in the HTML file. Within the <body>, the JavaScript appears after the <input> element, which has an id attribute.
2/ CSS elements
<style>
input {
padding: 8px;
border: 2px solid #ccc;
border-radius: 4px;
outline: none;
}
input.valid { border-color: green; }
input.invalid { border-color: red; }
#hint { font-size: 14px; color: gray; }
</style>Here, input is an element selector that applies the CSS ruleset to every <input> element in the document. Two additional rulesets use the combined selectors input.valid and input.invalid, targeting <input> elements with the valid and invalid classes, respectively. Finally, #hint is an ID selector, not a class selector. It applies its ruleset to the element whose ID is hint.
3/ JS method with DOM
<script>
const input = document.getElementById("username");
const hint = document.getElementById("hint"); input.addEventListener("input", (e) => {
const value = e.target.value.trim();
if (value.length === 0) {
input.classList.remove("valid", "invalid");
hint.textContent = "please input username";
hint.style.color = "gray";
} else if (value.length < 3) {
input.classList.add("invalid");
input.classList.remove("valid");
hint.textContent = `still needs ${3 - value.length} characters`;
hint.style.color = "red";
} else {
input.classList.add("valid");
input.classList.remove("invalid");
hint.textContent = "✓ username available";
hint.style.color = "green";
}
});
</script>
Two references, input and hint, are created for the corresponding HTML DOM elements. An input event listener is attached to the input field so that its callback runs whenever the field’s content changes.
Inside the callback, e.target.value.trim() retrieves the current input value and removes leading and trailing whitespace. Based on the length of this value, JavaScript adds or removes the predefined valid and invalid classes, causing the corresponding CSS rules to be applied. At the same time, the hint element’s text and color are updated through its textContent and style.color properties.
4/ QA
Q: Could you explain in more detail how an event listener works?
A: In the JavaScript world, the programming involves two sides: server and client. The event listener in this case is built in client’s browser. An event listener tells the browser to watch an HTML element for a specific event and execute a callback function when that event occurs.
Let’s read this example code:
input.addEventListener("input", (e) => {
console.log(e.target.value);
});This works as following steps:

• input refers to the HTML input element.

• addEventListener() registers an event listener with the browser.

• "input" specifies the event to monitor. It occurs whenever the user changes the field’s content.

• (e) => { ... } is the callback function.

• When the event occurs, the browser calls the callback and passes it an event object named e.

• e.target refers to the element that triggered the event.

• e.target.value contains the input field’s current value.
In the 3rd step, the "input" is a predefined event. The browser fires this event whenever the value of an <input> or <textarea> changes through user interaction, such as:

• Typing a character

• Deleting a character

• Pasting text

• Cutting text
Along with "input" , other predefined events include: "click", "change", "focus", "blur", "submit", "keydown".
